        <h2>What is diabetes?</h2>
        <p>
            Diabetes is a chronic disease that occurs when your blood sugar levels are too high. The food you eat is broken down into sugar (i.e., glucose) and released into your blood stream. When the glucose levels in your blood increase, it signals your pancreas to release insulin which allows your cells to uptake that glucose for energy. Occasionally, your body does not make enough insulin or the insulin it makes doesn't work as well as it should. This means the glucose lingers in the bloodstream instead of getting used up by the cells and this condition is known as diabetes. There are 3 main forms of diabetes:
        </p>
        <br>
        <h2>Type 1 Diabetes</h2>
        <p>
            Type 1 diabetes, also known as juvenile diabetes, is an autoimmune disease where the immune system targets the insulin producing cells in the pancreas resulting in little to no insulin production. It typically occurs in young adults however it can appear at any age. People with type 1 diabetes need to take insulin regularly in order to survive.

        </p>
        <br>
        <h2>Type 2 Diabetes</h2>
        <p>
            Type 2 diabetes is the most common type of diabetes. It is where the body becomes resistant to the effects of insulin and gradually looses the ability to produce enough insulin in the pancreas. The cause of type 2 diabetes is still being researched but recent evidence suggests that it is an autoimmune disease rather than a metabolic disorder. You are more likely to develop type 2 diabetes if you are physically inactive.

        </p>
        <br>
        <h2>Gestational Diabetes</h2>
        <p>
            Gestational diabetes develops during pregnancy when the body cannot manufacture the required amount of insulin. Pregnancy causes the body to make more hormones and go through changes such as weight gain. These changes cause your body to use insulin less effectively which leads to gestational diabetes. They typically resolve soon after the delivery of the baby.

        </p>
